     9→Abstract
    10→Large language models (LLMs) frequently
    11→make errors when handling even simple numer-
    12→ical problems, such as comparing two small
    13→numbers. A natural hypothesis is that these
    14→errors stem from how LLMs represent num-
    15→bers, and specifically, whether their represen-
    16→tations of numbers capture their numeric val-
    17→ues. We tackle this question from the obser-
    18→vation that LLM errors on numerical tasks are
    19→often distributed across the digits of the answer
    20→rather than normally around its numeric value.
    21→Through a series of probing experiments and
    22→causal interventions, we show that LLMs inter-
    23→nally represent numbers with individual circu-
    24→lar representations per-digit in base 10. This
    25→digit-wise representation, as opposed to a value
    26→representation, sheds light on the error patterns
    27→of models on tasks involving numerical reason-
    28→ing and could serve as a basis for future studies
    29→on analyzing numerical mechanisms in LLMs.
    30→1
    31→Introduction
    32→Despite their high performance on various challeng-
    33→ing tasks (Bubeck et al., 2023; Bommasani et al.,
    34→2021; Trinh et al., 2024), large language models
    35→(LLMs) often struggle with simple numerical prob-
    36→lems, such as adding or comparing the magnitude
    37→of two small numbers. While previous works com-
    38→monly attribute such failures to different limitations
    39→in the representations of LLMs (e.g., McLeish et al.,
    40→2024; Nogueira et al., 2021), how LLMs represent
    41→numbers is still an outstanding question.
    42→Recently, Zhu et al. (2024) used linear probes to
    43→predict the number encoded in a hidden represen-
    44→tation, showing high correlation with the expected
    45→value. However, the probes exhibited low accuracy,
    46→suggesting that a linear representation alone is not
    47→sufficient to explain how LLMs can often perform
    48→exact numerical operations, such as addition and
    49→multiplication. Maltoni and Ferrara (2024) have
