  1054→A
  1055→Additional Results
  1056→A.1
  1057→Error patterns of GPT-4o
  1058→We conducted an additional error analysis using
  1059→GPT-4o (OpenAI et al., 2024) on 15-operand addi-
  1060→tion tasks. Increasing the number of operands was
  1061→necessary due to the model’s high accuracy on sim-
  1062→pler addition problems. The results were consistent
  1063→with the trends observed in Figure 2, showing the
  1064→majority of errors are at multiples of 10, as seen in
  1065→Figure 4. This indicates that the fragmented error
  1066→distribution identified in smaller models persists in
  1067→larger models.
  1068→Increasing the number of digits instead of the
  1069→number of operands leads to errors in multiples
  1070→of 100 and 1,000 as well, showing that the error
  1071→distribution stays indicative of a fragmented repre-
  1072→sentation also for other digits.
  1073→A.2
  1074→PCA of hidden representations
  1075→We visualized the hidden states for natural number
  1076→tokens 0 to 999 in layer 2 of Llama 3 8B, projected
  1077→onto their top two principal components. In Fig-
  1078→ure 5 we can see that there are two half circles,
  1079→one contained at the edge of the other. One is a
  1080→half circle of all the numbers, and the next is of all
  1081→numbers 0-99.
  1082→An interesting observation is that within each
  1083→half-circle, the numbers increase in a clockwise
  1084→direction, indicating that the model may represent
  1085→digits circularly. In the circle for the numbers 0-99,
  1086→the numbers increase clockwise, and again when
  1087→you look at the half-circle that contains the rest
  1088→of the numbers. This indicates that at least the
  1089→hundreds digits and tens digits are represented cir-
  1090→cularly.
  1091→In Figure 6 we can see that the circular pattern
  1092→in the tens digit also extends to all numbers 0 to
  1093→999, when the dominance of the hundreds digit is
  1094→9
  1095→
  1096→
  1097→===== CHUNK 4 (2 pages) =====
  1098→removed through averaging out all numbers into 10
  1099→groups by their tens digit.
  1100→Figure 5: Visualization of the hidden states for natural
  1101→number tokens (0 to 999) in layer 2 of Llama 3 8B,
  1102→projected onto their top two principal components.
  1103→Figure 6: Visualization of the averaged hidden states
  1104→for natural number tokens (0 to 999), grouped by their
  1105→tens digit (0—9), in layer 5 of Llama 3 8B, projected
  1106→onto their top two principal components. For example,
  1107→numbers like 101 and 406, both having a tens digit of 0,
  1108→are grouped together.
  1109→A.3
  1110→Accuracy of circular probes
  1111→In the main results we showed the accuracy of the
  1112→circular digit-wise probes, averaged over layers
  1113→≥3. Here we will show this choice is justified
  1114→as can be seen in Figure 7. While there is signifi-
  1115→cant variations between layers, the accuracy is espe-
  1116→cially low before the contextualization that happens
  1117→in the first 3 layers.
  1118→Another interesting question is which layer’s set
  1119→of digit-wise circular-probes have the highest ac-
  1120→curacy in predicting the number, and how accurate
  1121→is it. The corresponding results can be seen in Ta-
  1122→ble 3. It can be observed that in Mistral 7B, in
  1123→the best layer, the circular probes achieve perfect
  1124→accuracy on the validation set. That is, the number
  1125→can always be recreated perfectly.
