  1150→Probing representations of numbers in
  1151→word form
  1152→Since numbers can also be represented in word
  1153→form, i.e. twenty-two for the number 22, we fur-
  1154→ther tested if our digit-wise circular probes extend
  1155→to these representations, without being explicitly
  1156→trained on them. Concretely, we evaluated the
  1157→probes’ accuracy for Llama 3 8B on the numbers
  1158→’zero’ through ’fifty’ in word form.
  1159→We observe that the accuracy varies depending
  1160→on the layer used, with a peak of 68.6 accuracy
  1161→when using the representations at layer 14. This is
  1162→an encouraging sign that the circular probes gener-
  1163→alize beyond the specific setting they were trained
  1164→on, which further supports our causal results.
  1165→B
  1166→Causal Intervention Details
  1167→We provide additional details on the interventions
  1168→performed in §3.3. In practice, since the two di-
  1169→rections of the circular probe are approximately
  1170→orthogonal, we project the hidden representation
  1171→onto each direction, subtract these components to
  1172→remove the original digit representation, and then
  1173→add the components back with their directions re-
  1174→versed to modify the digit. We also scaled the
  1175→projection by a fixed constant (a = 19), assum-
  1176→ing that if the model has multiple representations
  1177→for numbers, scaling the representation will make
  1178→the model place more weight upon it. The exact
  1179→constant was chosen through binary search, in or-
  1180→der to select the largest scaling factor such that the
  1181→model still predicts a number, as it was observed
  1182→that with a very high scaling factor the model starts
  1183→predicting non-numeric tokens.
