    31→INTRODUCTION
    32→One major limitation of large language models (LLMs) is their inability to guarantee factually pre-
    33→cise and correct outputs. This is a fundamental trait due to the probabilistic nature of transformer
    34→models, and thus not a solvable problem, as has recently been emphasized by (Kalai et al., 2025).
    35→However, knowing the extent of the problem (and whether it can be mitigated) is a feasible task; one
    36→that is important given the recent ubiquity of LLMs in research and broader society.
    37→Mathematical problems provide an ideal playground in which to assess the current ability of LLMs
    38→to manipulate precise information. Because it operates through a set of formal rules and produces
    39→computationally verifiable outputs, mathematics provides the opportunity to rate not only the ten-
    40→dency of a model to output incoherent information (Sun et al., 2024), but also to examine in detail
    41→the coherence of the reasoning steps outputted by a given LLM. While this research direction is rife
    42→with challenges, ranging from manipulating implicitly visual data in geometry problems (Ahn et al.,
    43→2024) to mapping plain language onto specific types of problems (Duchnowski et al., 2025), it has
    44→also been met by genuine successes, e.g., as an aid to solve mathematical problems (Li et al., 2025).
    45→A large body of work has highlighted limitations of LLMs when it comes to arithmetic tasks (Xu
    46→et al., 2025; Kvinge et al., 2025; Satpute et al., 2024; Lee et al., 2025; Bertolazzi et al., 2025;
    47→Nikankin et al., 2025), which in turn has led to various proposals to alleviate these limitations cen-
    48→tered on re-designing numeric representations to be principled and precise (e.g., Charton, 2022; Feng
    49→et al., 2024; Golkar et al., 2023). More recent developments have suggested that the issues models
    50→1
    51→arXiv:2510.26285v1  [cs.CL]  30 Oct 2025
    52→
    53→ArXiv pre-print
    54→encounter with arithmetic need not be tied to the quality of their representations of numbers. Several
    55→works have attempted to characterize the types of representations models rely on to perform arith-
    56→metic computations (Wennberg & Henter, 2024; Zhou et al., 2024a; Zhu et al., 2025; Kadlˇc´ık et al.,
    57→2025). This research direction has proposed that number representations stand out in terms of their
    58→structure, with Zhou et al. (2024a) and Kadlˇc´ık et al. (2025) arguing that models rely on sinusoidal
    59→structures, whereas Zhu et al. (2025) suggest that representations are better described using a linear
    60→model than a multi-layer perceptron. These results have also been combined with observations as to
    61→how models process and succeed at arithmetic tasks.
    62→In this paper, we provide evidence that LLMs converge to systematic and accurate sinusoidal rep-
    63→resentations that are maintained throughout the model in different forms. These representations are
    64→largely equivalent across LLMs of different sizes and families. Building upon this, we find that
    65→numeric information from LLMs can be accurately extracted using universal probes and show that
    66→more accurate numeric probes allow us to attribute up to 94% of model errors in arithmetical rea-
    67→soning to particular layers, overriding the existing, correct results.1
