    69→RELATED WORK
    70→Math capabilities of LLMs
    71→The seminal remarks of Brown et al. (2020) that LLMs that are large
    72→enough develop arithmetic capabilities have ushered in a large body of work aimed at evaluating the
    73→mathematical capabilities of LLMs (Hendrycks et al., 2021; Cobbe et al., 2021; Sun et al., 2024;
    74→Yu et al., 2024) or lack thereof (Nikankin et al., 2025). This in turn has encouraged a focus on
    75→how to bolster the capabilities of LLMs or interpret how LLMs perform computations (Zhang et al.,
    76→2024; Stolfo et al., 2023). Most relevant to ours, some of the previous work especially focuses on
    77→how numbers should be represented in principle. For instance, Charton (2022) assess an impact on
    78→models performance in linear algebra problems when employing different encoding schemes based
    79→on scientific notation on linear algebra problems. Golkar et al. (2023) propose to encode numeric
    80→values by incorporating a scaled, learned control token <NUM>. Feng et al. (2024) remark that the
    81→precision of the numeric representation type impacts performance on arithmetic tasks, and argue to
    82→use the logarithmic-precision architecture of Feng et al. (2023).
    83→Numeric representations in LLMs
    84→The increased focus on evaluating LLM performance in veri-
    85→fiable domains such as math problems has also led to increased interest in the mechanisms by which
    86→LLMs compute arithmetic functions. Nanda et al. (2023) demonstrate how a model trained from
    87→scratch on modular addition relies on trigonometric operation: it maps inputs onto a unit circle,
    88→corresponding to a specific rotation, and then learns to combine the two rotations to derive a valid
    89→solution. Kantamneni & Tegmark (2025) apply circuit analysis to highlight how general pretrained
    90→models perform addition, and highlight that representations are mapped onto a helix that can be
    91→manipulated using trigonometric operations. Zhou et al. (2024b) recast these observations in terms
    92→of Fourier components (since Fourier transformations map arbitrary functions unto combinations of
    93→periodic trigonometric functions), and highlight the distinct role of attention and feedforward sub-
    94→layers. Focusing more narrowly on representations rather than processing, Zhu et al. (2025) argue
    95→that non-linear probes do not provide a better fit than linear probes. Levy & Geva (2025) remark that
    96→it is possible to retrieve the digit (value mod 10) of numeric inputs with high accuracy. Kadlˇc´ık et al.
    97→(2025) propose a linear probe architecture that factors in the sinusoidal nature of the embeddings of
    98→numbers, and show that they can retrieve numeric precision with high accuracy.
    99→In summary, there is a growing body of evidence stating that models rely on trigonometric represen-
   100→tations for numbers. Here, we build upon Kadlˇc´ık et al. (2025) specifically, as the high accuracy of
   101→their proposed probe provides new opportunities and novel research directions — as we find, also in
   102→tracking and verifying the accuracy of a model’s inner representations throughout its computations,
   103→robust across contexts, model types and operations.
