   110→UNIVERSALITY OF SINUSOIDAL REPRESENTATIONS OF NUMBERS
   111→3.1
   112→MODELS LEARN EQUIVALENT REPRESENTATIONS OF NUMBERS
   113→The first point we address is the distinctiveness of LLMs’ representations of numbers. Results from
   114→Kadlˇc´ık et al. (2025) and Zhu et al. (2025) suggest that different models converge to the same type
   115→of number representations, but they do not provide a direct assessment of how closely the represen-
   116→tations match across models – which could evidence that a shared representation is a causal conse-
   117→quence of architectural bias and optimization process rather than a coincidental artifact. Following
   118→Kadlˇc´ık et al., we focus on the input embeddings from eight LLMs of diverse sizes and families with
   119→open-sourced, pre-trained checkpoints: OLMo 2 (OLMo et al., 2025), Llama 3 (Grattafiori et al.,
   120→2024) and Phi 4 (Abdin et al., 2024).
   121→(a) Cosine-based RSA for number tokens
   122→(b) Cosine-based RSA for random tokens
   123→Figure 1: Representational similarity analysis (RSA) scores
   124→To quantify whether models converge to similar embeddings, we start by conducting a simple Rep-
   125→resentational Similarity Analysis (RSA; Kriegeskorte et al., 2008) across the input embeddings for
   126→number word-pieces in paired models.2 As a baseline, we compute RSA scores for a random sam-
   127→ple of 1000 pieces present in the vocabularies of all the models under consideration. Results of the
   128→analysis are displayed in Figure 1. Across all pairs of models, we find that number embeddings
   129→systematically yield higher RSA scores than a random sample of word pieces. While some mod-
   130→els (especially in the Phi family) are not as well aligned with other models, we do observe high
   131→scores both within and across families, demonstrating that models converge to embedding spaces
   132→with equivalent similarity structure.
   133→Another approach to quantifying the similarity of frequential representations characteristic for num-
   134→bers Kadlˇc´ık et al. (2025); Zhou et al. (2024a) is by inspecting their base frequencies through Fourier
   135→decompositions. Applying a PCA transformation followed by a Fourier transform allows us to quan-
   136→tify the magnitude of individual frequencies (Figure 2a). Subsequently, we determine whether two
   137→models agree as to how they rank frequencies by computing a simple intersection-over-union (IoU)
   138→of the top k frequencies. We repeat this process for every pair of models, using the input embed-
   139→dings of number pieces (Figure 2b) as well as that of random pieces as previously (Figure 2c). When
   140→considering the top k = 63 frequencies,3 we find perfect agreement across all models in terms of
   141→number pieces.
   142→In summary, our analyses show that the LLMs from different families learn to represent numbers in
   143→a similar topology and trigonometric features using the same dominant frequencies. This is specific
   144→to numbers – we do not reproduce these observations with other word pieces shared across models.
   145→2RSA is a second-order similarity measurement. Let A = {a1, . . . an} and B = {b1, . . . bn} be two
   146→sets of matching representations, in our case the input embeddings for number word-pieces in two models
   147→θA and θB. We can assess the extent to which A and B encode the same type of similarity structures by
   148→simply computing the (Spearman) correlation ρsA,sB, where sA = (cos(a1, a2) . . . cos(an−1, an)) and sB =
   149→(cos(b1, b2) . . . cos(bn−1, bn)) are two vectors tracking all pairwise similarities within A and B respectively.
