   183→where Win and Wout are learned parameters, and S injects an inductive bias in the classifier towards
   184→sinusoidal representations. We build upon an assumption verified by Kadlˇc´ık et al. (2025) stating
   185→that sinusoidal probes indeed adapt and employ a sinusoidal representation from inductive bias, if a
   186→sinusoidal representation is also present in the input embeddings.
   187→We first assess whether sinusoidal probes are the most suitable, i.e., an accurate choice for decoding
   188→the internal representations of the model. To contextualize the accuracy in terms of sinusoidal
   189→quality of the representation, we also evaluate other types of probes used to decode numbers in
   190→previous work Feng et al. (2023); Zhu et al. (2025); Kadlˇc´ık et al. (2025) as baselines. we train the
   191→sinusoidal probe on hidden representations of each layer of Llama 3.2 1B model when processing
   192→addition prompts of the form ‘x1 + x2’, where x1 and x2 are integers. We specifically evaluate
   193→whether the value of x2 can be retrieved from the model’s hidden representation on each layer. To
   194→assess generalization rather than memorization capacity, we split the prompts and corresponding
   195→representations into training, validation and test sets containing distinct extracted numbers (x2).
   196→Figure 3a shows the accuracy of different probes extracting the value of input numbers from rep-
   197→resentations of each model’s layer, evaluated across six different models. The superior accuracy of
   198→sinusoidal probe provides an indicator of both (i) the sinusoidal character, and (ii) accuracy of input
   199→number representation across layers.
   200→Thus far, an important caveat of ours, as well as a methodology of previous work probing represen-
   201→tations of numbers in previous work (section 2) is that we focus on a very specific type of input,
   202→namely additions, without any sort of natural language to contextualize them. As such, it is reason-
   203→able to assume that the results presented in Figure 3 may not carry to a more natural context: there
   204→is little guarantee that the behavior of a model on arithmetic problems is indicative of its behavior a
   205→broad range of applications requiring manipulations of numbers in natural language contexts.
