   242→sentations, we curate a dataset covering four domains involving intensive numeric manipulations:
   243→arithmetic (mathematical word problems), temporal (date extraction), medical (ICD-10 diagnostic
   244→codes) and culinary (recipe ingredients/quantities). The complete dataset specifications are detailed
   245→in Table 1 in Section B. To maximize the quality of learned probes and thus, representativeness of
   246→our findings, we also tackle the natural-language class imbalance; as not every number has equal
   247→probability to occur in a date or in a recipe, we replace original numbers with integers uniformly
   248→sampled from the model vocabulary. We then fit separate probes for activations from every layer,
   249→again holding out a set of 100 randomly selected numbers for evaluating generalization.
   250→Fig. 3b displays the accuracies of input value extraction from model’s hidden states within natural-
   251→language contexts across six LLMs of different sizes and three different families. As we can see,
   252→the sinusoidal probes reach over 70% of accuracy in all but three cases and over 90% of accuracy
   253→for a majority of probing scenarios. Taking into an account that the learned sinusoidal probe also
   254→induce a certain error. Therefore, these accuracies present a lower-bound of accuracy of models’
   255→representation of input numbers in natural contexts in a sinusoidal representation — showing that
   256→the accurate, sinusoidal representation is indeed characteristic and employed by a wide range of
   257→recent language models.
