   344→heldout-layer fashion, reaching an accuracy between 95 and 100% across all intermediate layers and
   345→three models of diverse sizes and families. This result has practical implications for future work
   346→in numeric interpretability — showing that we can train universal, yet highly accurate probes for
   347→intermediate layers of a broad set of language models4.
   348→Cross-layer evaluation indicates that models’ internal representations tend to differ from the in-
   349→put/output embeddings.
   350→We find a notable discrepancy in the sparsity of their representation;
   351→Whereas the input/output embeddings represent numbers in a more distributed fashion, hidden lay-
   352→ers use a small number of consistently-ordered sin features.
   353→This is visualized in Figure 6, showing that intermediate layers in Llama 1B lead to probes with very
   354→few weights with values > 10−5.
