  1009→A.1
  1010→SELECTING THE OPTIMAL NUMBER OF FOURIER COMPONENTS FOR COMPARISON
  1011→Figure 12: Minimum IoU across number of frequencies considered
  1012→In Section 3.1, we discuss selecting the optimal number of Fourier components. As can be assessed
  1013→from 2a, from a certain frequency rank, Fourier decompositions resort to noise. Thus, our objective
  1014→is to find the “cutoff” rank (k) that disentangles oscillating information from the non-oscillating,
  1015→presumably non-numeric information. This means finding an optimal, yet non-trivial (e.g. ≥10)
  1016→cutoff for a number of components. In practice, we evaluate for each value of k what the minimum
  1017→IoU agreement score across all models amounts to for numbers and random overlapping word-
  1018→pieces. As displayed in Figure 12, we find such an optimal cutoff at k = 63 as the highest value of
  1019→k that leads to perfect agreement across models.
  1020→A more thorough assessment of Figure 12 suggests a few interesting trends. Random word pieces
  1021→also tend to favor a handful of Fourier basis components; which we conjecture is due to the sampling
  1022→mechanism. By selecting overlapping pieces, our pieces must be frequent enough to be present in
  1023→multiple distinct tokenizers, which in turns shapes the type of linguistic units represented in this
  1024→random sample. Secondly, we also observe a ‘cross-over’ point around k ≈250, after which we
  1025→find greater agreement in random pieces than numbers. Yet, we note that (i) a significant proportion
  1026→of the mass is concentrated in a few frequency components for numbers, whereas random pieces lead
  1027→to much more uniform distributions across frequeny components; and (ii) the results in Figure 12
  1028→still allow us to establish that the Fourier profile of number pieces is clearly dsitinct from what we
  1029→observe for any other overlapping set of word pieces.
