   162→3.2
   163→NUMBER REPRESENTATIONS ARE ALWAYS SINUSOIDAL
   164→In subsection 3.1, we presented evidence that the input embeddings of numbers in LLMs have cer-
   165→tain properties related to how they encode numeric information, such as being sinusoidal. In this
   166→section, we aim to find whether such representations are also maintained and employed throughout
   167→the models.
   168→For qualitative assessment, we visualize the PCA and its Fourier transform of internal activations of
   169→numerical tokens in Section A.3. Besides the apparent wave-like pattern, the representations have
   170→a sparse Fourier transform, confirming the sinusoidal character. For quantitative analysis, we look
   171→at the model’s internal representations through the lens of the sinusoidal probe proposed by Kadlˇc´ık
   172→et al. (2025). This probe was designed to map input embeddings of LLMs into an integer, thus
   173→classifying embeddings into predefined range of numeric values. The sinusoidal probe is defined as:
