   304→3.3
   305→DIFFERENT LAYERS USE INTERCHANGEABLE NUMERIC REPRESENTATIONS
   306→Having found the remarkable degree to which the embeddings for numbers align across different
   307→models and the noteworthy universality of sinusoidal representations in varied contexts, we turn to
   308→further analyses assessing the extent to which these structures are utilized by the models. First, we
   309→address whether the same sinusoidal structure is conserved across a model’s computations.
   310→To that end, we employ the probes we developed in Section 3.2 trained separately for each model
   311→layer, Li, and measure the accuracy of each probe on representations derived for every other layer
   312→Lj ̸= Li. This approach, while informative, comes with the caveat that probes trained for a given
   313→layer Li might pick up on idiosyncrasies inherent to a specific layer — i.e., the probes might not
   314→disentangle what is specific to numbers as opposed to what is specific to a layer. To address this
   315→point, we also fit probes using all but one layer (L1, L2, . . . Li−1, Li+1, . . . Ln), and evaluate the
   316→performance on representations from the held out layer Li. As previously, we hold out a subset of
   317→100 numbers for assessing generalization in validation and test conditions.
