   466→MECHANISMS OF NUMBER MANIPULATION
   467→We have established that models converge to sinusoidal number representations universally. This
   468→naturally begs the question of how those sinusoidal representations are used.
   469→4.1
   470→MULTI-TOKEN NUMBERS
   471→Our first point of order concerns digits beyond the range of what can be represented in recent LLMs
   472→with a single token. To see whether LMs are able to represent even the values of multi-token numbers
   473→systematically and accurately, we probe the values of all parts of multi-token numbers from a single
   474→representation corresponding to the last numeric token. The accuracy of this experiment uncovers the
   475→extent to which the models implement a systematic algorithm of superposing multi-token numbers
   476→in a single representation.
   477→For this experiment, we adapt the methodology utilizing natural-language contexts, with a substitu-
   478→tion of original numeric values with values spanning two to six numeric tokens, i.e. in a numeric
   479→range between 103 −1018. We use a subset of BBC data that was published after the knowledge
   480→cutoff or release date of all the models under consideration (Li et al., 2024).5
   481→To be able to contextualize the magnitude of superposition and thus, disentangle a general model
   482→mechanism from the mechanism specific for numbers, we also probe representations of natural-
   483→language tokens using TunedLens (Belrose et al., 2025). TunedLens is an early-exit interpretability
   484→method which aims to explain the contents of intermediate representations by learning to translate
   485→them into logits. In practice, for each layer Li, TunedLens involves distilling the computations done
   486→in the subsequent layers Li+1, . . . Ln into a simple affine transformation Wi, such that applying
   487→this transformation Wi to a hidden state at Li followed by the unembedding matrix closely matches
   488→the logits that the LLM would eventually produce. Here, to maximize comparability and align the
   489→number and distribution of target categories, we narrow down the space of probed tokens to 1000
   490→tokens (matching the number probes) ranked as 2000–3000thmost-common tokens in our dataset.
   491→Results for Llama 1B and different probing methods are presented in Figure 7. Results of sin probes
   492→show that multi-token numbers are indeed systematically and highly accurately superposed in
   493→the latest numeric representation – reaching an accuracy of 99% for the immediately-preceding
   494→number piece (offset -1). However, the accuracy and/or systematicity of the superposition mecha-
   495→nism quickly drops for numbers longer than three tokens (i.e. ≥109), reaching close to zero for the
   496→5th preceding token.
   497→The results of natural-language token probing using TunedLens reveal that superpositioning repre-
   498→sentations of previous tokens is not a mechanism specific only to numbers – albeit this mechanism
   499→seems more prevalent and accurate for numeric tokens. Aiming to maximise comparability, we
   500→also report a comparison of the previous-token recovery using TunedLens for numeric tokens —
   501→in exactly the same configuration as for the natural-language tokens. This comparison shows that
   502→TunedLens is highly inefficient for recovering numeric tokens compared to sinusoidal probes.
   503→4.2
   504→ERROR TRACKING
   505→Establishing that LLMs use universal, systematic and interchangeable representations of numbers,
   506→we aim to explore whether we can build upon this knowledge in tracing the origins of models’ out-
   507→puts in arithmetic reasoning. First, we assess the predictive power of models’ internal representations
   508→towards true results in prompts requiring addition, subtraction, multiplication and division.
   509→Results of predicting the Llama 3.2 3B’s expected outputs for different operations are displayed
   510→in Figure 9. We can see a large distinction between the cases where the model predicts a correct
   511→and incorrect response – suggesting that the extent to which the model maintains the sinusoidal
   512→representation may determine the accuracy of the output. We observe that for addition and
   513→subtraction, probes can, with close to 100% accuracy, identify the retrieved result already from
   514→the model internals. Based on qualitative assessments of output embeddings (subsection B.1), we
   515→hypothesise that lower reliability in other operations (multiplication and division) may be caused by
