   699→CONCLUSIONS
   700→Building upon the recent advancements in probing techniques, this paper builds a fundamental un-
   701→derstanding of how LLMs internally represent and manipulate numeric values. We provide evidence
   702→that diverse LLMs learn and employ mutually-interchangeable, consistent sinusoidal representations
   703→across their internal layers, maintained largely by residual streams, but distinct in the embedding rep-
   704→resentation and internal activations in terms of sparsity. We show how probing techniques respecting
   705→representational properties of numbers open up new possibilities for tracking the causes of errors in
   706→models’ internal computation, attributing large portions of errors to numeric interventions of con-
   707→crete layers. Towards the fast-growing field of interpretability research, our work contributes by
   708→evidencing the importance of natural-language probes in training better-generalising probes or the
   709→superior quality of specialised probes compared to widely-used methods such as linear or TunedLens
   710→probes. We hope that our work clearly outlines the potential of more accurate probes in robustness
   711→and faithfulness assessments of existing and future reasoning models.
